    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>Jany 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1846</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <add>באין תחבלות יפל עם ותשועה ברב יועץ</add>
            </p>
            <p>Revd Sir,I trust that the purport of my letter will<lb/> be a sufficient excuse for
                thus intruding on your valuable time.<lb/> You are aware that I am the Secretary of
                the Congregation<lb/> “Shanarai Chased”, which congregation I have but lately<lb/>
                joined; I did so thinking that I might perhaps be of service<lb/> to them, after the
                division made, by the fen-Portuguese Members.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">A case of peculiar interest is now before the Congregations and<lb/>
                I wish your opinion and instructions on the subject. It is as follows.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">A gentleman—a very old and long inhabitant of this City,<lb/>
                    (<persName>Mr Alexander Phillips</persName>) married according to Christian <hi
                    rend="underline">rites</hi>,<lb/> a Christian woman; he has a large family by
                this <hi rend="underline">Christian</hi><lb/> wife; his sons have not been made
                Hebrews; neither has his<lb/> sons or daughters been christened or baptized; and I
                do believe<lb/> that they have all been brought up to believe themselves Jews &amp;
                Jewesses.<lb/> A daughter of this <sic>gentlemen</sic> and Christian woman has
                lately<lb/> been engaged to be married to an Israelite (<persName>Mr
                    Haber</persName>) and the<lb/> parties wish the marriage to be solemnized in
                this Congregation,<lb/> I am of the opinion, and have so stated, that the girl must
                go<lb/> through the regular and complete forms, requisite to make a<lb/>
                <add>גיורת</add>, and such was the unanimous opinion of most of the Israelites<lb/>
                in this place. I am sorry to say that I think money has induced<lb/> these people to
                alter their opinion; they have also told me that a</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>a person whom they say is <add>רב</add> in <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>, has
                decided,<lb/> that as the lady is of an Hebrew father, and, in consideration<lb/>
                that she has never been baptized &amp;c; it is not necessary for her to<lb/> go
                through the forms to make her a <add>גיורת</add>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Not knowing the<lb/> gentleman of <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>,
                I respectfully beg of you to give me<lb/> the particulars (plain) of what has to be
                done. For this is<lb/> a matter in which all <placeName>Israel</placeName> is
                concerned; for if we do<lb/> not keep a sharp look out, we will become so
                intermixed<lb/> with strangers, that it must cause great confusion in our ranks</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">I am Reverend Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">Yours Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">Benjamin W: Cohen</persName>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Revd I: Leeser</addressee>.</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
